item.title: Hear 'Mad Butcher' Ed Gein's voice for first time in new docuseries
item.description: Explore More A new docuseries about OG serial killer Ed Gein offers fresh insight into the mind of “The Mad Butcher” — told, in parts, by Gein himself in never-before-heard audiotapes. “Psycho: The Lost Tapes of Ed Gein,” premiering Sept. 17 on MGM+, uses the tapes, unearthed in 2019, to delve into the mind of Gein, who was arrested in November 1957 in desolate Plainfield, WI. Authorities entering his woodshed and adjoining house discovered a horrific scene: human heads; furniture, lamps and mugs fashioned out of human skin and skulls; human face masks; a heart in a frying pan; a belt made of nipples; and the body of a local woman, Bernice Worden, hanging in Gein’s woodshed — gutted and dismembered like a dead deer.

item.title: Catnip Tea for Cats: How to Make It, Benefits, Recipe & More
item.description: Catnip (Nepeta cataria) is a wild perennial plant that you can find growing in almost any well-drained soil, particularly in disturbed areas and along habitat edges. The ingredient that gives it its distinctive smell is nepetalactone. This compound serves a vital function for these plants by repelling insects. Interestingly, the chemical disappeared early in the evolutionary history of the genus, only to re-emerge later. New evidence suggests that it can have a similar use for humans as a chemical that is even more effective than DEET.

It prided itself on providing viewers with half an hour of sanctuary from the turbulent social and political upheaval of the 1960s. Consequently, it’s not surprising that the show isn’t widely recognized for groundbreaking depictions of women.
